Furthermore, some say that Solon got an oracle at Pytho which ran as follows:—
Take thy seat amidships, the pilot’s task is thine;
Perform it, many in Athens are thine allies. And above all, his familial friends chid him for being averse to absolute power because of the name of tyranny, as if the virtues of him who seized it would not at once make it a lawful sovereignty. Euboea (they argued) had formerly found this true of Tynnondas, and so had the Mitylenaeans, now that they had chosen Pittacus to be their tyrant.
